---
import CodeBlock from "../CodeBlock.astro";
---

<section class="jr-section" id="voice">
  <div class="jr-section-body">
    <div class="jr-intro">
      <p class="jr-kicker">Voice and writing</p>
      <h2 class="jr-heading">Direct, useful, joyful.</h2>
      <p class="jr-copy">
        Riot’s Jolly Roger sounds direct, opinionated, useful, technical, and
        joyful. It does not sound corporate, academic, generic, or clever when
        a clear label helps more.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="guideline-rows">
      <article class="guideline-row" id="voice-direct">
        <p class="jr-label">Direct</p>
        <h3 class="jr-subheading">Say the thing.</h3>
        <p class="jr-copy">
          Do not wrap every claim in hedging language. Do not make the reader
          decode vague platform words. Do not hide the action behind narrative.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="guideline-row" id="voice-useful">
        <p class="jr-label">Useful</p>
        <h3 class="jr-subheading">Every sentence should help.</h3>
        <p class="jr-copy">
          A page can be joyful, opinionated, or expressive, but it still has to
          help the reader install Riot, find a package, fix an error,
          understand a module, compare options, or keep moving.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="guideline-row" id="voice-joyful">
        <p class="jr-label">Joyful</p>
        <h3 class="jr-subheading">Joy means momentum.</h3>
        <p class="jr-copy">
          Joy does not mean childish. The writing should make the reader feel
          that Riot is on their side: beautiful code, fast feedback, good
          defaults, visible power, and the pleasure of building useful software.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="guideline-row" id="voice-errors">
        <p class="jr-label">Errors</p>
        <h3 class="jr-subheading">Clear, structured, recoverable.</h3>
        <div class="guideline-prose">
          <p>
            Error copy starts with the problem. Name what failed before
            explaining how the system works, then give the reader enough
            context to recover without guessing.
          </p>
          <p>
            A useful Riot error names the package, source, requested thing,
            expected or available thing, and the reason it happened when that
            reason is known. It ends with one concrete command, edit, or docs
            link. The same diagnostic should still make sense as plain text.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="guideline-row" id="voice-agents">
        <p class="jr-label">Agents</p>
        <h3 class="jr-subheading">Stable labels. No guessing.</h3>
        <div class="guideline-prose">
          <p>
            Agent-ready voice is still human voice. It just refuses to hide
            important state in loose prose. When a surface describes a package,
            command, file, error, or generated report, name the stable facts
            directly so a person can scan them and a tool can parse them.
          </p>
          <p>
            Prefer labels such as package, source, wanted, found, and fix when
            those facts matter. Make examples reusable without hidden setup.
            Avoid copy that forces the reader to infer the package, file,
            requested symbol, or next command.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>

    <div class="guideline-example-set" id="voice-example">
      <p class="jr-label">Example</p>
      <p class="jr-copy">
        Vague copy names no object, no source, and no recovery path. It leaves
        both humans and agents guessing.
      </p>
      <CodeBlock label="Vague">Something went wrong while resolving dependencies.</CodeBlock>

      <p class="jr-copy">
        Better copy names the package, explains the failure, and gives the next
        command.
      </p>
      <CodeBlock label="Better">Riot could not resolve Krasny because riot-cli does not depend on the package that exposes it.

Run riot add krasny.</CodeBlock>

      <p class="jr-copy">
        When the output is meant for tools too, expose the same facts as stable
        fields.
      </p>
      <CodeBlock label="Preferred structure">package: riot-cli
source:  src/publish.ri
wanted:  Krasny
fix:     riot add krasny</CodeBlock>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
